<h1>Online Bible: New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures</h1>
</noscript>
<p class="title">Genesis 25:1-34</p>
<form class="formtext">
<input type="hidden" name="chapterCount" value="50">
<input type="hidden" name="verseCount" value="34">
<p><a name="bk1" class="vsAnchor">1</a>
       <span id="vs1">Furthermore, Abraham again took a wife, and her name was Ke&middot;tu&acute;rah.</span> <a name="bk2" class="vsAnchor">2</a>
       <span id="vs2">In time she bore him Zim&acute;ran and Jok&acute;shan and Me&acute;dan and Mid&acute;i&middot;an and Ish&acute;bak and Shu&acute;ah.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk3" class="vsAnchor">3</a>
       <span id="vs3">And Jok&acute;shan became father to She&acute;ba and De&acute;dan.</span>
</p>

<p> 
       <span id="vs3-2">And the sons of De&acute;dan became As&middot;shu&acute;rim and Le&middot;tu&acute;shim and Le&middot;um&acute;mim.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk4" class="vsAnchor">4</a>
       <span id="vs4">And the sons of Mid&acute;i&middot;an were E&acute;phah and E&acute;pher and Ha&acute;noch and A&middot;bi&acute;da and El&middot;da&acute;ah.</span>
</p>

<p> 
       <span id="vs4-2">All these were the sons of Ke&middot;tu&acute;rah.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk5" class="vsAnchor">5</a>
       <span id="vs5">Later on Abraham gave everything he had to Isaac,</span> <a name="bk6" class="vsAnchor">6</a>
       <span id="vs6">but to the sons of the concubines that Abraham had Abraham gave gifts. Then he sent them away from Isaac his son, while he was still alive, eastward, to the land of the East.</span> <a name="bk7" class="vsAnchor">7</a>
       <span id="vs7">And these are the days of the years of Abraham’s life which he lived, a hundred and seventy-five years.</span> <a name="bk8" class="vsAnchor">8</a>
       <span id="vs8">Then Abraham expired and died in a good old age, old and satisfied, and was gathered to his people.</span> <a name="bk9" class="vsAnchor">9</a>
       <span id="vs9">So Isaac and Ish&acute;ma&middot;el his sons buried him in the cave of Mach&middot;pe&acute;lah in the field of E&acute;phron the son of Zo&acute;har the Hit&acute;tite that is in front of Mam&acute;re,</span> <a name="bk10" class="vsAnchor">10</a>
       <span id="vs10">the field that Abraham had purchased from the sons of Heth. There Abraham was buried, and also Sarah his wife.</span> <a name="bk11" class="vsAnchor">11</a>
       <span id="vs11">And it developed that after Abraham’s death God continued to bless Isaac his son, and Isaac was dwelling close by Be&acute;er-la&acute;hai-roi.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk12" class="vsAnchor">12</a>
       <span id="vs12">And this is the history of Ish&acute;ma&middot;el the son of Abraham whom Ha&acute;gar the Egyptian the maidservant of Sarah bore to Abraham.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk13" class="vsAnchor">13</a>
       <span id="vs13">Now these are the names of the sons of Ish&acute;ma&middot;el, by their names, according to their family origins: Ish&acute;ma&middot;el’s firstborn Ne&middot;ba&acute;ioth and Ke&acute;dar and Ad&acute;be&middot;el and Mib&acute;sam</span> <a name="bk14" class="vsAnchor">14</a>
       <span id="vs14">and Mish&acute;ma and Du&acute;mah and Mas&acute;sa,</span> <a name="bk15" class="vsAnchor">15</a>
       <span id="vs15">Ha&acute;dad and Te&acute;ma, Je&acute;tur, Na&acute;phish and Ked&acute;e&middot;mah.</span> <a name="bk16" class="vsAnchor">16</a>
       <span id="vs16">These are the sons of Ish&acute;ma&middot;el, and these are their names by their courtyards and by their walled camps: twelve chieftains according to their clans.</span> <a name="bk17" class="vsAnchor">17</a>
       <span id="vs17">And these are the years of Ish&acute;ma&middot;el’s life, a hundred and thirty-seven years. Then he expired and died and was gathered to his people.</span> <a name="bk18" class="vsAnchor">18</a>
       <span id="vs18">And they took up tabernacling from Hav&acute;i&middot;lah near Shur, which is in front of Egypt, as far as As&middot;syr&acute;i&middot;a. In front of all his brothers he settled down.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk19" class="vsAnchor">19</a>
       <span id="vs19">And this is the history of Isaac the son of Abraham.</span>
</p>

<p> 
       <span id="vs19-2">Abraham became father to Isaac.</span> <a name="bk20" class="vsAnchor">20</a>
       <span id="vs20">And Isaac happened to be forty years old at his taking Re&middot;bek&acute;ah the daughter of Be&middot;thu&acute;el the Syrian of Pad&acute;dan-a&acute;ram, the sister of La&acute;ban the Syrian, as his wife.</span> <a name="bk21" class="vsAnchor">21</a>
       <span id="vs21">And Isaac kept on entreating Jehovah especially for his wife, because she was barren; so Jehovah let himself be entreated for him, and Re&middot;bek&acute;ah his wife became pregnant.</span> <a name="bk22" class="vsAnchor">22</a>
       <span id="vs22">And the sons within her began to struggle with each other, so that she said: “If this is the way it is, just why am I alive?” With that she went to inquire of Jehovah.</span> <a name="bk23" class="vsAnchor">23</a>
       <span id="vs23">And Jehovah proceeded to say to her: “Two nations are in your belly, and two national groups will be separated from your inward parts; and the one national group will be stronger than the other national group, and the older will serve the younger.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk24" class="vsAnchor">24</a>
       <span id="vs24">Gradually her days came to the full for giving birth, and, look! twins were in her belly.</span> <a name="bk25" class="vsAnchor">25</a>
       <span id="vs25">Then the first came out red all over like an official garment of hair; so they called his name E&acute;sau.</span> <a name="bk26" class="vsAnchor">26</a>
       <span id="vs26">And after that his brother came out and his hand was holding onto the heel of E&acute;sau; so he called his name Jacob. And Isaac was sixty years old at her giving them birth.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk27" class="vsAnchor">27</a>
       <span id="vs27">And the boys got bigger, and E&acute;sau became a man knowing how to hunt, a man of the field, but Jacob a blameless man, dwelling in tents.</span> <a name="bk28" class="vsAnchor">28</a>
       <span id="vs28">And Isaac had love for E&acute;sau, because it meant game in his mouth, whereas Re&middot;bek&acute;ah was a lover of Jacob.</span> <a name="bk29" class="vsAnchor">29</a>
       <span id="vs29">Once Jacob was boiling up some stew, when E&acute;sau came along from the field and he was tired.</span> <a name="bk30" class="vsAnchor">30</a>
       <span id="vs30">So E&acute;sau said to Jacob: “Quick, please, give me a swallow of the red—the red there, for I am tired!” That is why his name was called E&acute;dom.</span> <a name="bk31" class="vsAnchor">31</a>
       <span id="vs31">To this Jacob said: “Sell me, first of all, your right as firstborn!”</span> <a name="bk32" class="vsAnchor">32</a>
       <span id="vs32">And E&acute;sau continued: “Here I am simply going to die, and of what benefit to me is a birthright?”</span> <a name="bk33" class="vsAnchor">33</a>
       <span id="vs33">And Jacob added: “Swear to me first of all!” And he proceeded to swear to him and to sell his right as firstborn to Jacob.</span> <a name="bk34" class="vsAnchor">34</a>
       <span id="vs34">And Jacob gave E&acute;sau bread and lentil stew, and he went to eating and drinking. Then he got up and went his way. So E&acute;sau despised the birthright.</span>
</p>
</form>

<script language="JavaScript1.2" type="text/javascript">
